you know LEN already trims right? However datalength doesn&#039;t&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
DECLARE @d CHAR(10) =&#039;123 &#039;&lt;br /&gt;
SELECT LEN(@d), DATALENGTH(@d)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
--------&lt;br /&gt;
3	10&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
there is also a difference for unicode&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
DECLARE @d NCHAR(10) =&#039;123 &#039;&lt;br /&gt;
SELECT LEN(@d), DATALENGTH(@d)&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
--------&lt;br /&gt;
3	20&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Datalength can also be used with text and ntext columns&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
See also &lt;a href=&quot;/index.php/DataMgmt/DBProgramming/the-differences-between-len-and-dataleng&quot;&gt;The differences between LEN and DATALENGTH in SQL Server&lt;/a&gt;
